        <h4><b>The problem</b></h4>
        <p>As someone who has a Gluten free restricted diet, I often found myself searching through magazines, blogs and online stores to find places to eat out, to shop and to discover new home recipes. This proved to be time consuming and often results with limited success.</p> 
<p>Therefore, I decided to investigate whether this was a common issue and if so, whether I could develop a potential solution.</p>
        <hr>
        <h4><b>Research</b></h4>
        <h5>Desktop research</h5>
        <p>I began my investigation by carrying out desktop research. I initially explored gluten free recipe books as well as magazines. Later, I searched through app stores such as IOS app store and Android app store. Websites with terms including ‘Gluten Free’, ‘food apps’, ‘recipe apps’ and ‘restaurant finder apps’. 
At each stage of this research, I was able to build knowledge of the content the various sources were publishing as well as building familiarity with the phases and imagery used. 
With each source of information, I read reviews to further understand the aims of readers and users and also to discover where perhaps it did not meet their expectations. 
</p>
        <p>Apps I reviewed included: </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Gluten free heaven</li>
          <li>How to be Gluten free and keep your friends </li>
          <li>Simple Vegan: Recipes and Guides</li>
          <li>Find Me Gluten Free</li>
          <li>Meals - Healthy meal planner</li>
        </ul>
