        <h5>Interviews</h5>
        <p>Following the desktop research, I carried out qualitative research, in the form of interviews, on individuals who follow a Gluten Free diet. These interviews allowed me to identify the needs of those who follow a gluten free diet as well as some of their problems.
        </p>
        <p>Some of the questions used in the interviews included:</p>
        <ol>
  <li>What are your reasons for following a Gluten Free diet?</li>
  <li>What do you enjoy most about following a Gluten Free diet? </li>
  <li>What do you find most difficult about following a Gluten Free diet?</li>
</ol>
<h5>Analysing results</h5>
<p>To help make sense of my findings, I grouped common problems through the tool of an affinity map. 
From this exercise, I was able to identify two key problems which had the greatest impact on the majority of those who I interviewed. The critical problems I identified are:</p>
   <ol>
  <li><b>It takes too long to find information</b> - the majority of interviewees mentioned that they found it time consuming searching across various platforms to find gluten free recipes, products and restaurants </li>
  <li><b>There are many varied sources of information to navigate</b> - much of the information from a particular source, was often specialised in one area. For example most books and magazines focused on home cooking recipes but paid little attention in describing where to source ingredients. </li>
</ol>
